# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: encryption-at-rest
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] BitLocker originated as a part of Microsoft's Next-Generation Secure Computing Base architecture in 2004 as a feature tentatively codenamed "Cornerstone" and was designed to protect information on devices, particularly if a device was lost or stolen.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Another feature, titled "Code Integrity Rooting", was designed to validate the integrity of Microsoft Windows boot and system files.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] When used in conjunction with a compatible Trusted Platform Module (TPM), BitLocker can validate the integrity of boot and system files before decrypting a protected volume; an unsuccessful validation will prohibit access to a protected system.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] BitLocker was briefly called Secure Startup before Windows Vista's release to manufacturing.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Initially, the graphical BitLocker interface in Windows Vista could only encrypt the operating system volume.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Starting with Windows Vista with Service Pack 1 and Windows Server 2008, volumes other than the operating system volume could be encrypted using the graphical tool.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Still, some aspects of the BitLocker (such as turning autolocking on or off) had to be managed through a command-line tool called `manage-bde.wsf`.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] The version of BitLocker included in Windows 7 and Windows Server 2008 Release 2 adds the ability to encrypt removable drives.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] On Windows XP or Windows Vista, read-only access to these drives can be achieved through a program called BitLocker To Go Reader, if FAT16, FAT32 or exFAT filesystems are used.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] In addition, a new command-line tool called `manage-bde` replaced the old `manage-bde.wsf`.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Starting with Windows Server 2012 and Windows 8, Microsoft has complemented BitLocker with the Microsoft Encrypted Hard Drive specification, which allows the cryptographic operations of BitLocker encryption to be offloaded to the storage device's hardware, for example, self-encrypting drives.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] In addition, BitLocker can now be managed through Windows PowerShell.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Finally, Windows 8 introduced Windows To Go in its Enterprise edition, which BitLocker can protect.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Windows Mobile 6.5, Windows RT and core editions of Windows 8.1 include **device encryption**, a feature-limited version of BitLocker that encrypts the whole system.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Logging in with a Microsoft account with administrative privileges automatically begins the encryption process.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] The recovery key is stored to either the Microsoft account or Active Directory (Active Directory requires Pro editions of Windows), allowing it to be retrieved from any computer.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] While device encryption is offered on all editions of Windows 8.1, unlike BitLocker, device encryption requires that the device meet the InstantGo (formerly Connected Standby) specifications, which requires solid-state drives and a TPM 2.0 chip.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Starting with Windows 10 1703, the requirements for device encryption have changed, requiring a TPM 1.2 or 2.0 module with PCR 7 support, UEFI Secure Boot, and that the device meets Modern Standby requirements or HSTI validation.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Device encryption requirements were relaxed in Windows 11 24H2, with the Modern Standby, HSTI and Secure Boot compliance no longer required and the DMA interfaces blocklist removed.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] And device encryption will be enabled by default by clean installation of Windows 11 24H2, called *auto device encryption*.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] In September 2019 a new update was released (KB4516071) changing the default setting for BitLocker when encrypting a self-encrypting drive.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Now, the default is to use software encryption for newly encrypted drives.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] This is due to hardware encryption flaws and security concerns related to those issues.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] BitLocker is a logical volume encryption system.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] (A volume spans part of a hard disk drive, the whole drive or more than one drive.) When enabled, TPM and BitLocker can ensure the integrity of the trusted boot path (e.g.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] BIOS and boot sector), in order to prevent most offline physical attacks and boot sector malware.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] In order for BitLocker to encrypt the volume holding the operating system, at least two NTFS-formatted volumes are required: one for the operating system (usually C:) and another with a minimum size of 100 MB, which remains unencrypted and boots the operating system.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] A tool called the BitLocker Drive Preparation Tool is also available from Microsoft that allows an existing volume on Windows Vista to be shrunk to make room for a new boot volume and for the necessary bootstrapping files to be transferred to it.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Once an alternate boot partition has been created, the TPM module needs to be initialized (assuming that this feature is being used), after which the required disk-encryption key protection mechanisms such as TPM, PIN or USB key are configured.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] The volume is then encrypted as a background task, something that may take a considerable amount of time with a large disk as every logical sector is read, encrypted and rewritten back to disk.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] The keys are only protected after the whole volume has been encrypted when the volume is considered secure.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] BitLocker uses a low-level device driver to encrypt and decrypt all file operations, making interaction with the encrypted volume transparent to applications running on the platform.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Encrypting File System (EFS) may be used in conjunction with BitLocker to provide protection once the operating system is running.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Protection of the files from processes and users within the operating system can only be performed using encryption software that operates within Windows, such as EFS.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] BitLocker and EFS, therefore, offer protection against different classes of attacks.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] In Active Directory environments, BitLocker supports optional key escrow to Active Directory, although a schema update may be required for this to work (i.e. if the Active Directory Services are hosted on a Windows version previous to Windows Server 2008).
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] BitLocker and other full disk encryption systems can be attacked by a rogue boot manager.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Once the malicious bootloader captures the secret, it can decrypt the Volume Master Key (VMK), which would then allow access to decrypt or modify any information on an encrypted hard disk.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] By configuring a TPM to protect the trusted boot pathway, including the BIOS and boot sector, BitLocker can mitigate this threat.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] The "Transparent operation mode" and "User authentication mode" of BitLocker use TPM hardware to detect whether there are unauthorized changes to the pre-boot environment, including the BIOS and MBR.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] If any unauthorized changes are detected, BitLocker requests a recovery key on a USB device.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] This cryptographic secret is used to decrypt the Volume Master Key (VMK) and allow the bootup process to continue.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] All these attacks require physical access to the system and are thwarted by a secondary protector such as a USB flash drive or PIN code.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Although the AES encryption algorithm used in BitLocker is in the public domain, its implementation in BitLocker, as well as other components of the software, are proprietary; however, the code is available for scrutiny by Microsoft partners and enterprises, subject to a non-disclosure agreement.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] According to Microsoft sources, BitLocker does not contain an intentionally built-in backdoor, so there is no Microsoft-provided way for law enforcement to have guaranteed access to the data on a user's drive.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] In 2006, the UK Home Office expressed concern over the lack of a backdoor and tried entering into talks with Microsoft to get one introduced.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Microsoft developer and cryptographer Niels Ferguson denied the backdoor request and said, "over my dead body".
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Niels Ferguson's position that "back doors are simply not acceptable" is in accordance with Kerckhoffs's principle.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Stated by Netherlands-born cryptographer Auguste Kerckhoffs in the 19th century, the principle holds that a cryptosystem should be secure, even if everything about the system, except the encryption key, is public knowledge.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Since 2014, BitLocker's method and data structure is public knowledge due to reverse engineering; the Linux dislocker program is capable of reading and writing BitLocker-protected drives given the key; since 2020, this can also be done with cryptsetup.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Starting with Windows 8 and Windows Server 2012, Microsoft removed the Elephant Diffuser from the BitLocker scheme.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Dan Rosendorf's research shows that removing the Elephant Diffuser had an "undeniably negative impact" on the security of BitLocker encryption against a targeted attack.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Microsoft later cited performance concerns, and noncompliance with the Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS), to justify the diffuser's removal.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Starting with Windows 10 version 1511, however, Microsoft added a new FIPS-compliant XTS-AES encryption algorithm to BitLocker.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Starting with Windows 10 version 1803, Microsoft added a new feature called "Kernel Direct Memory access (DMA) Protection" to BitLocker, to protect against DMA attacks via Thunderbolt 3 ports.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] "Kernel Direct Memory access (DMA) Protection" only protects against attacks through Thunderbolt.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Direct Memory Access is also possible through PCI Express.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] In this type of attack an attacker would connect a malicious PCI Express Device, which can in turn write directly to the memory and bypass the Windows login.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] To protect against this type of attack, Microsoft introduced "Virtualization-based Security".
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] In October 2017, it was reported that a flaw enabled private keys to be inferred from public keys, which could allow an attacker to bypass BitLocker encryption when an affected TPM chip is used.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] The flaw is the Return of Coppersmith's Attack (ROCA) vulnerability which is in a code library developed by Infineon and had been in widespread use in security products such as smartcards and TPMs.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Microsoft released an updated version of the firmware for Infineon TPM chips that fixes the flaw via Windows Update.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] In May 2026, a security researcher, operating under the "Chaotic Eclipse" pseudonym, disclosed a method of bypassing BitLocker, which he dubbed YellowKey.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] This vulnerability, now officially acknowledged as CVE-2026-45585, affects only Windows 11, Windows Server 2022, and Windows Server 2025.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] The older Windows 10 remains unaffected.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] Microsoft released a mitigation for this threat on 22 May, and promised a fix in the June 2026 update, but did not take kindly to its exposure.
[src:encryption-at-rest/bitlocker] The company threatened legal action against Chaotic Eclipse for uncoordinated disclosure of the vulnerability, deleted his GitHub repositories demonstrating the vulnerability, and suspended his GitHub account.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] This article provides a simple model to follow when implementing solutions to protect data at rest.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Passwords should not be stored using reversible encryption - secure password hashing algorithms should be used instead.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The Password Storage Cheat Sheet contains further guidance on storing passwords.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The first step in designing any application is to consider the overall architecture of the system, as this will have a huge impact on the technical implementation.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] This process should begin with considering the threat model of the application (i.e, who you are trying to protect that data against).
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Note that many cloud environments provide these services, so these should be taken advantage of where possible.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The Secrets Management Cheat Sheet contains further guidance on this topic.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Which layer(s) are most appropriate will depend on the threat model.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For example, hardware level encryption is effective at protecting against the physical theft of the server, but will provide no protection if an attacker is able to compromise the server remotely.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The best way to protect sensitive information is to not store it in the first place.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Although this applies to all kinds of information, it is most often applicable to credit card details, as they are highly desirable for attackers, and PCI DSS has such stringent requirements for how they must be stored.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Wherever possible, the storage of sensitive information should be avoided.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For symmetric encryption **AES** with a key that's at least **128 bits** (ideally **256 bits**) and a secure mode should be used as the preferred algorithm.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For asymmetric encryption, use elliptical curve cryptography (ECC) with a secure curve such as **Curve25519** as a preferred algorithm.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] If ECC is not available and **RSA** must be used, then ensure that the key is at least **2048 bits**.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Many other symmetric and asymmetric algorithms are available which have their own pros and cons, and they may be better or worse than AES or Curve25519 in specific use cases.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] In some cases there may be regulatory requirements that limit the algorithms that can be used, such as FIPS 140-2 or PCI DSS.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] There are various modes that can be used to allow block ciphers (such as AES) to encrypt arbitrary amounts of data, in the same way that a stream cipher would.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] These modes have different security and performance characteristics, and a full discussion of them is outside the scope of this cheat sheet.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Some of the modes have requirements to generate secure initialisation vectors (IVs) and other attributes, but these should be handled automatically by the library.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Where available, authenticated modes should always be used.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] These provide guarantees of the integrity and authenticity of the data, as well as confidentiality.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The most commonly used authenticated modes are **GCM** and **CCM**, which should be used as a first preference.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] If GCM or CCM are not available, then CTR mode or CBC mode should be used.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] As these do not provide any guarantees about the authenticity of the data, separate authentication should be implemented, such as using the Encrypt-then-MAC technique.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] ECB should not be used outside of very specific circumstances.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For RSA, it is essential to enable Random Padding.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Random Padding is also known as OAEP or Optimal Asymmetric Encryption Padding.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] This class of defense protects against Known Plain Text Attacks by adding randomness at the beginning of the payload.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The Padding Schema of PKCS#1 is typically used in this case.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Random numbers (or strings) are needed for various security critical functionality, such as generating encryption keys, IVs, session IDs, CSRF tokens or password reset tokens.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] As such, it is important that these are generated securely, and that it is not possible for an attacker to guess and predict them.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] It is generally not possible for computers to generate truly random numbers (without special hardware), so most systems and languages provide two different types of randomness.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Pseudo-Random Number Generators (PRNG) provide low-quality randomness that are much faster, and can be used for non-security related functionality (such as ordering results on a page, or randomising UI elements).
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] However, they **must not** be used for anything security critical, as it is often possible for attackers to guess or predict the output.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Cryptographically Secure Pseudo-Random Number Generators (CSPRNG) are designed to produce a much higher quality of randomness (more strictly, a greater amount of entropy), making them safe to use for security-sensitive functionality.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] However, they are slower and more CPU intensive, can end up blocking in some circumstances when large amounts of random data are requested.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] As such, if large amounts of non-security related randomness are needed, they may not be appropriate.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The table below shows the recommended algorithms for each language, as well as insecure functions that should not be used.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Universally unique identifiers (UUIDs or GUIDs) are sometimes used as a quick way to generate random strings.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Although they can provide a reasonable source of randomness, this will depend on the type or version of the UUID that is created.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Specifically, version 1 UUIDs are comprised of a high precision timestamp and the MAC address of the system that generated them, so are **not random** (although they may be hard to guess, given the timestamp is to the nearest 100ns).
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Type 4 UUIDs are randomly generated, although whether this is done using a CSPRNG will depend on the implementation.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Unless this is known to be secure in the specific language or framework, the randomness of UUIDs should not be relied upon.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Applications should be designed to still be secure even if cryptographic controls fail.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Any information that is stored in an encrypted form should also be protected by additional layers of security.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Application should also not rely on the security of encrypted URL parameters, and should enforce strong access control to prevent unauthorised access to information.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Keys should be randomly generated using a cryptographically secure function, such as those discussed in the Secure Random Number Generation section.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Keys **should not** be based on common words or phrases, or on "random" characters generated by mashing the keyboard.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Where multiple keys are used (such as data separate data-encrypting and key-encrypting keys), they should be fully independent from each other.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Once one of these criteria have been met, a new key should be generated and used for encrypting any new data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Marking each item with the ID of the key that was used to encrypt it, and storing multiple keys to allow the old data to be decrypted.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The first option should generally be preferred, as it greatly simplifies both the application code and key management processes; however, it may not always be feasible.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Note that old keys should generally be stored for a certain period after they have been retired, in case old backups of copies of the data need to be decrypted.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] It is important that the code and processes required to rotate a key are in place **before** they are required, so that keys can be quickly rotated in the event of a compromise.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Additionally, processes should also be implemented to allow the encryption algorithm or library to be changed, in case a new vulnerability is found in the algorithm or implementation.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Securely storing cryptographic keys is one of the hardest problems to solve, as the application always needs to have some level of access to the keys in order to decrypt the data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] While it may not be possible to fully protect the keys from an attacker who has fully compromised the application, a number of steps can be taken to make it harder for them to obtain the keys.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Where available, the secure storage mechanisms provided by the operating system, framework or cloud service provider should be used.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] There are many advantages to using these types of secure storage over simply putting keys in configuration files.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] In some cases none of these will be available, such as in a shared hosting environment, meaning that it is not possible to obtain a high degree of protection for any encryption keys.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The Secrets Management Cheat Sheet provides more details on securely storing secrets.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Where possible, encryption keys should be stored in a separate location from encrypted data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For example, if the data is stored in a database, the keys should be stored in the filesystem.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] This means that if an attacker only has access to one of these (for example through directory traversal or SQL injection), they cannot access both the keys and the data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Depending on the architecture of the environment, it may be possible to store the keys and data on separate systems, which would provide a greater degree of isolation.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Where possible, encryption keys should themselves be stored in an encrypted form.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For this to be effective, the KEK must be stored separately from the DEK.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The encrypted DEK can be stored with the data, but will only be usable if an attacker is able to also obtain the KEK, which is stored on another system.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The KEK should also be at least as strong as the DEK.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The envelope encryption guidance from Google contains further details on how to manage DEKs and KEKs.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] In simpler application architectures (such as shared hosting environments) where the KEK and DEK cannot be stored separately, there is limited value to this approach, as an attacker is likely to be able to obtain both of the keys at the same time.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] However, it can provide an additional barrier to unskilled attackers.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] A key derivation function (KDF) could be used to generate a KEK from user-supplied input (such a passphrase), which would then be used to encrypt a randomly generated DEK.
[src:encryption-at-rest/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] This allows the KEK to be easily changed (when the user changes their passphrase), without needing to re-encrypt the data (as the DEK remains the same).
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Digital data can be contrasted with *analog data*, which is represented by a value from a continuous range of real numbers.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Analog data is transmitted by an analog signal, which not only takes on continuous values but can vary continuously with time, a continuous real-valued function of time.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] An example is the air pressure variation in a sound wave.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Data requires interpretation to become information.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] In modern (post-1960) computer systems, all data is digital.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] The word *digital* comes from the same source as the words digit and *digitus* (the Latin word for *finger*), as fingers are often used for counting.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Mathematician George Stibitz of Bell Telephone Laboratories used the word *digital* in reference to the fast electric pulses emitted by a device designed to aim and fire anti-aircraft guns in 1942.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] The term is most commonly used in computing and electronics, especially where real-world information is converted to binary numeric form as in digital audio and digital photography.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Since symbols (for example, alphanumeric characters) are not continuous, representing symbols digitally is rather simpler than conversion of continuous or analog information to digital.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Instead of sampling and quantization as in analog-to-digital conversion, such techniques as polling and encoding are used.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] A symbol input device usually consists of a group of switches that are polled at regular intervals to see which switches are switched.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Data will be lost if, within a single polling interval, two switches are pressed, or a switch is pressed, released, and pressed again.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] This polling can be done by a specialized processor in the device to prevent burdening the main CPU.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] When a new symbol has been entered, the device typically sends an interrupt, in a specialized format, so that the CPU can read it.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] For devices with only a few switches (such as the buttons on a joystick), the status of each can be encoded as bits (usually 0 for released and 1 for pressed) in a single word.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] This is useful when combinations of key presses are meaningful, and is sometimes used for passing the status of modifier keys on a keyboard (such as shift and control).
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] But it does not scale to support more keys than the number of bits in a single byte or word.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Devices with many switches (such as a computer keyboard) usually arrange these switches in a scan matrix, with the individual switches on the intersections of x and y lines.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] When a switch is pressed, it connects the corresponding x and y lines together.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Polling (often called scanning in this case) is done by activating each x line in sequence and detecting which y lines then have a signal, thus which keys are pressed.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] When the keyboard processor detects that a key has changed state, it sends a signal to the CPU indicating the scan code of the key and its new state.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] The symbol is then encoded or converted into a number based on the status of modifier keys and the desired character encoding.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] A custom encoding can be used for a specific application with no loss of data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] However, using a standard encoding such as ASCII is problematic if a symbol such as 'ß' needs to be converted but is not in the standard.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] It is estimated that in the year 1986, less than 1% of the world's technological capacity to store information was digital and in 2007 it was already 94%.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] The year 2002 is assumed to be the year when humankind was able to store more information in digital than in analog format (the "beginning of the digital age").
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Digital data come in these three states: data at rest, data in transit, and data in use.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] The confidentiality, integrity, and availability have to be managed during the entire lifecycle from 'birth' to the destruction of the data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] While it is generally accepted that archive data (i.e. which never changes), regardless of its storage medium, is data at rest and active data subject to constant or frequent change is data in use. “Inactive data” could be taken to mean data which may change, but infrequently.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] The imprecise nature of terms such as “constant” and “frequent” means that some stored data cannot be comprehensively defined as either data at rest or in use.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] These definitions could be taken to assume that Data at Rest is a superset of data in use; however, data in use, subject to frequent change, has distinct processing requirements from data at rest, whether completely static or subject to occasional change.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Because of its nature data at rest is of increasing concern to businesses, government agencies and other institutions.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Data encryption, which prevents data visibility in the event of its unauthorized access or theft, is commonly used to protect data in motion and increasingly promoted for protecting data at rest.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] The encryption of data at rest should only include strong encryption methods such as AES or RSA.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Encrypted data should remain encrypted when access controls such as usernames and password fail.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Increasing encryption on multiple levels is recommended.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Cryptography can be implemented on the database housing the data and on the physical storage where the databases are stored.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Data encryption keys should be updated on a regular basis.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Encryption keys should be stored separately from the data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Encryption also enables crypto-shredding at the end of the data or hardware lifecycle.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Periodic auditing of sensitive data should be part of policy and should occur on scheduled occurrences.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Finally, only store the minimum possible amount of sensitive data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Tokenization is a non-mathematical approach to protecting data at rest that replaces sensitive data with non-sensitive substitutes, referred to as tokens, which have no extrinsic or exploitable meaning or value.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] This process does not alter the type or length of data, which means it can be processed by legacy systems such as databases that may be sensitive to data length and type.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Tokens require significantly less computational resources to process and less storage space in databases than traditionally encrypted data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] This is achieved by keeping specific data fully or partially visible for processing and analytics while sensitive information is kept hidden.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Lower processing and storage requirements makes tokenization an ideal method of securing data at rest in systems that manage large volumes of data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] A further method of preventing unwanted access to data at rest is the use of data federation especially when data is distributed globally (e.g. in off-shore archives).
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] An example of this would be a European organisation which stores its archived data off-site in the US.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Under the terms of the USA PATRIOT Act the American authorities can demand access to all data physically stored within its boundaries, even if it includes personal information on European citizens with no connections to the US.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Data encryption alone cannot be used to prevent this as the authorities have the right to demand decrypted information.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] A data federation policy which retains personal citizen information with no foreign connections within its country of origin (separate from information which is either not personal or is relevant to off-shore authorities) is one option to address this concern.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] However, data stored in foreign countries can be accessed using legislation in the CLOUD Act.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Some cloud software as a service (SaaS) providers refer to data in use as any data currently being processed by applications, as the CPU and memory are utilized.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Because of its nature, data in use is of increasing concern to businesses, government agencies and other institutions.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Data in use, or memory, can contain sensitive data including digital certificates, encryption keys, intellectual property (software algorithms, design data), and personally identifiable information.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Compromising data in use enables access to encrypted data at rest and data in motion.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] For example, someone with access to random access memory can parse that memory to locate the encryption key for data at rest.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Once they have obtained that encryption key, they can decrypt encrypted data at rest.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Threats to data in use can come in the form of cold boot attacks, malicious hardware devices, rootkits and bootkits.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Encryption, which prevents data visibility in the event of its unauthorized access or theft, is commonly used to protect Data in Motion and Data at Rest and increasingly recognized as an optimal method for protecting Data in Use.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] There have been multiple projects to encrypt memory.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Microsoft Xbox systems are designed to provide memory encryption and the company PrivateCore presently has a commercial software product vCage to provide attestation along with full memory encryption for x86 servers.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Several papers have been published highlighting the availability of security-enhanced x86 and ARM commodity processors.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] In that work, an ARM Cortex-A8 processor is used as the substrate on which a full memory encryption solution is built.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Process segments (for example, stack, code or heap) can be encrypted individually or in composition.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] This work marks the first full memory encryption implementation on a mobile general-purpose commodity processor.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] The system provides both confidentiality and integrity protections of code and data which are encrypted everywhere outside the CPU boundary.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] For x86 systems, AMD has a Secure Memory Encryption (SME) feature introduced in 2017 with Epyc.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Intel has promised to deliver its Total Memory Encryption (TME) feature in an upcoming CPU.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Operating system kernel patches such as TRESOR and Loop-Amnesia modify the operating system so that CPU registers can be used to store encryption keys and avoid holding encryption keys in RAM.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] While this approach is not general purpose and does not protect all data in use, it does protect against cold boot attacks.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Encryption keys are held inside the CPU rather than in RAM so that data at rest encryption keys are protected against attacks that might compromise encryption keys in memory.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Enclaves enable an “enclave” to be secured with encryption in RAM so that enclave data is encrypted while in RAM but available as clear text inside the CPU and CPU cache.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Intel Corporation has introduced the concept of “enclaves” as part of its Software Guard Extensions.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Intel revealed an architecture combining software and CPU hardware in technical papers published in 2013.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Several cryptographic tools, including secure multi-party computation and homomorphic encryption, allow for the private computation of data on untrusted systems.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Data in use could be operated upon while encrypted and never exposed to the system doing the processing.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Data in transit can be separated into two categories: information that flows over the public or untrusted network such as the Internet and data that flows in the confines of a private network such as a corporate or enterprise local area network (LAN).
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Data within a computer, in most cases, moves as parallel data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Data moving to or from a computer, in most cases, moves as serial data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Data sourced from an analog device, such as a temperature sensor, may be converted to digital using an analog-to-digital converter.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Data representing quantities, characters, or symbols on which operations are performed by a computer are stored and recorded on magnetic, optical, electronic, or mechanical recording media, and transmitted in the form of digital electrical or optical signals.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Data pass in and out of computers via peripheral devices.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Physical computer memory elements consist of an address and a byte/word of data storage.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Digital data are often stored in relational databases, like tables or SQL databases, and can generally be represented as abstract key/value pairs.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Data can be organized in many different types of data structures, including arrays, graphs, and objects.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Data structures can store data of many different types, including numbers, strings and even other data structures.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Metadata helps translate data to information.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Metadata may be implied, specified or given.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Data relating to physical events or processes will have a temporal component.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] This is the case when a device such as a temperature logger receives data from a temperature sensor.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] When the temperature is received it is assumed that the data has a temporal reference of *now*.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] So the device records the date, time and temperature together.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] When the data logger communicates temperatures, it must also report the date and time as metadata for each temperature reading.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Fundamentally, computers follow a sequence of instructions they are given in the form of data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] A set of instructions to perform a given task (or tasks) is called a *program*.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] A program is data in the form of coded instructions to control the operation of a computer or other machine.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] In the nominal case, the program, as executed by the computer, will consist of machine code.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] The elements of storage manipulated by the program, but not actually executed by the central processing unit (CPU), are also data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] At its most essential, a single datum is a value stored at a specific location.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Therefore, it is possible for computer programs to operate on other computer programs, by manipulating their programmatic data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] To store data bytes in a file, they have to be serialized in a file format.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Typically, programs are stored in special file types, different from those used for other data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Executable files contain programs; all other files are also data files.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] However, executable files may also contain data used by the program which is built into the program.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] In particular, some executable files have a data segment, which nominally contains constants and initial values for variables, both of which can be considered data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] The line between program and data can become blurry.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] An interpreter, for example, is a program.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] The input data to an interpreter is itself a program, just not one expressed in native machine language.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] In many cases, the interpreted program will be a human-readable text file, which is manipulated with a text editor program.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Metaprogramming similarly involves programs manipulating other programs as data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Programs like compilers, linkers, debuggers, program updaters, virus scanners and such use other programs as their data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] For example, a user might first instruct the operating system to load a word processor program from one file, and then use the running program to open and edit a document stored in another file.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] In this example, the document would be considered data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] If the word processor also features a spell checker, then the dictionary (word list) for the spell checker would also be considered data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] The algorithms used by the spell checker to suggest corrections would be either machine code data or text in some interpretable programming language.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] In an alternate usage, binary files (which are not human-readable) are sometimes called *data* as distinguished from human-readable *text*.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] The total amount of digital data in 2007 was estimated to be 281 billion gigabytes (281 exabytes).
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Keys in data provide the context for values.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Regardless of the structure of data, there is always a key component present.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Keys in data and data-structures are essential for giving meaning to data values.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Without a key that is directly or indirectly associated with a value, or collection of values in a structure, the values become meaningless and cease to be data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] That is to say, there has to be a key component linked to a value component in order for it to be considered data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Random access memory (RAM) holds data that the CPU has direct access to.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] A CPU may only manipulate data within its processor registers or memory.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] This is as opposed to data storage, where the CPU must direct the transfer of data between the storage device (disk, tape...) and memory.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] RAM is an array of linear contiguous locations that a processor may read or write by providing an address for the read or write operation.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] The processor may operate on any location in memory at any time in any order.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] In RAM the smallest element of data is the binary bit.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] The capabilities and limitations of accessing RAM are processor specific.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] In general main memory is arranged as an array of locations beginning at address 0 (hexadecimal 0).
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Each location can store usually 8 or 32 bits depending on the computer architecture.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Data keys need not be a direct hardware address in memory.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Indirect, abstract and logical keys codes can be stored in association with values to form a data structure.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Data structures have predetermined offsets (or links or paths) from the start of the structure, in which data values are stored.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Therefore, the data key consists of the key to the structure plus the offset (or links or paths) into the structure.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] In such an organization of data, the data key is usually a value in one (or a composite of the values in several) of the columns.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] The tabular view of repeating data structures is only one of many possibilities.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Repeating data structures can be organised hierarchically, such that nodes are linked to each other in a cascade of parent-child relationships.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Values and potentially more complex data-structures are linked to the nodes.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Thus the nodal hierarchy provides the key for addressing the data structures associated with the nodes.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] This representation can be thought of as an inverted tree.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Modern computer operating system file systems are a common example; and XML is another.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Data has some inherent features when it is sorted on a key.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] All the values for subsets of the key appear together.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] When passing sequentially through groups of the data with the same key, or a subset of the key changes, this is referred to in data processing circles as a break, or a control break.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] It particularly facilitates the aggregation of data values on subsets of a key.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Until the advent of bulk non-volatile memory like flash, persistent data storage was traditionally achieved by writing the data to external block devices like magnetic tape and disk drives.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] These devices typically seek to a location on the magnetic media and then read or write blocks of data of a predetermined size.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] In this case, the seek location on the media, is the data key and the blocks are the data values.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Early used *raw disk* data file-systems or disc operating systems reserved contiguous blocks on the disc drive for data files.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] In those systems, the files could be filled up, running out of data space before all the data had been written to them.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Thus much unused data space was reserved unproductively to ensure adequate free space for each file.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Later file-systems introduced partitions.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] They reserved blocks of disc data space for partitions and used the allocated blocks more economically, by dynamically assigning blocks of a partition to a file as needed.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] To achieve this, the file system had to keep track of which blocks were used or unused by data files in a catalog or file allocation table.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Though this made better use of the disc data space, it resulted in fragmentation of files across the disc, and a concomitant performance overhead due additional seek time to read the data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Modern file systems reorganize fragmented files dynamically to optimize file access times.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Further developments in file systems resulted in virtualization of disc drives i.e. where a logical drive can be defined as partitions from a number of physical drives.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Retrieving a small subset of data from a much larger set may imply inefficiently searching through the data sequentially.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] **Indexes** are a way to copy out keys and location addresses from data structures in files, tables and data sets, then organize them using inverted tree structures to reduce the time taken to retrieve a subset of the original data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] In order to do this, the key of the subset of data to be retrieved must be known before retrieval begins.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] The most popular indexes are the B-tree and the dynamic hash key indexing methods.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Indexing is overhead for filing and retrieving data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] There are other ways of organizing indexes, e.g. sorting the keys and using a binary search algorithm.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] 2. at run time, the creation of references to in-memory data-structures of objects that have been instantiated from a class library.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] It is only after instantiation that an object of a specified class exists.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] After an object's reference is cleared, the object also ceases to exist.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] The memory locations where the object's data was stored are garbage and are reclassified as unused memory available for reuse.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] The advent of databases introduced a further layer of abstraction for persistent data storage.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Databases use metadata, and a structured query language protocol between client and server systems, communicating over a computer network, using a two phase commit logging system to ensure transactional completeness, when saving data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Modern scalable and high-performance data persistence technologies, such as Apache Hadoop, rely on massively parallel distributed data processing across many commodity computers on a high bandwidth network.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] In such systems, the data is distributed across multiple computers and therefore any particular computer in the system must be represented in the key of the data, either directly, or indirectly.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] This enables the differentiation between two identical sets of data, each being processed on a different computer at the same time.
[src:encryption-at-rest/data-at-rest] Even though digital signals are generally associated with the binary electronic digital systems used in modern electronics and computing, digital systems are actually ancient, and need not be binary or electronic.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Transparent data encryption (often abbreviated as TDE) is used to encrypt an entire database, which therefore involves encrypting "data at rest".
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Data at rest can generally be defined as "inactive" data that is not currently being edited or pushed across a network.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] As an example, a text file stored on a computer is "at rest" until it is opened and edited.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Data at rest are stored on physical storage media solutions such as tapes or hard disk drives.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] The act of storing large amounts of sensitive data on physical storage media naturally raises concerns of security and theft.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] TDE ensures that the data on physical storage media cannot be read by malicious individuals that may have the intention to steal them.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Data that cannot be read is worthless, thus reducing the incentive for theft.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Perhaps the most important strength that is attributed to TDE is its transparency.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Given that TDE encrypts all data it can be said that no applications need to be altered in order for TDE to run correctly.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] TDE encrypts the entirety of the database as well as backups of the database.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] The transparent element of TDE has to do with the fact that TDE encrypts on "the page level", which essentially means that data is encrypted when stored and decrypted when it is called into the system's memory.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] The contents of the database are encrypted using a symmetric key that is often referred to as a "database encryption key".
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] In order to explain column-level encryption it is important to outline basic database structure.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] A typical relational database is divided into tables that are divided into columns that each have rows of data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Whilst TDE usually encrypts an entire database, column-level encryption allows for individual columns within a database to be encrypted.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] It is important to establish that the granularity of column-level encryption causes specific strengths and weaknesses to arise when compared to encrypting an entire database.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Firstly, the ability to encrypt individual columns allows for column-level encryption to be significantly more flexible when compared to encryption systems that encrypt an entire database such as TDE.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Secondly, it is possible to use an entirely unique and separate encryption key for each column within a database.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] This effectively increases the difficulty of generating rainbow tables which thus implies that the data stored within each column is less likely to be lost or leaked.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] The main disadvantage associated with column-level database encryption is speed, or a loss thereof.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Encrypting separate columns with different unique keys in the same database can cause database performance to decrease, and additionally also decreases the speed at which the contents of the database can be indexed or searched.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Experimental work is being done on providing database operations (like searching or arithmetical operations) on encrypted fields without the need to decrypt them.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Strong encryption is required to be randomized - a different result must be generated each time.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] This is known as probabilistic encryption.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Field-level encryption is weaker than randomized encryption, but it allows users to test for equality without decrypting the data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] It is important to note that traditional database encryption techniques normally encrypt and decrypt the contents of a database.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Databases are managed by "Database Management Systems" (DBMS) that run on top of an existing operating system (OS).
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] This raises a potential security concern, as an encrypted database may be running on an accessible and potentially vulnerable operating system.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] EFS can encrypt data that is not part of a database system, which implies that the scope of encryption for EFS is much wider when compared to a system such as TDE that is only capable of encrypting database files.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Whilst EFS does widen the scope of encryption, it also decreases database performance and can cause administration issues as system administrators require operating system access to use EFS.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Due to the issues concerning performance, EFS is not typically used in databasing applications that require frequent database input and output.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] In order to offset the performance issues it is often recommended that EFS systems be used in environments with few users.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] BitLocker does not have the same performance concerns associated with EFS.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Symmetric encryption in the context of database encryption involves a private key being applied to data that is stored and called from a database.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] This private key alters the data in a way that causes it to be unreadable without first being decrypted.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Data is encrypted when saved, and decrypted when opened given that the user knows the private key.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Thus if the data is to be shared through a database the receiving individual must have a copy of the secret key used by the sender in order to decrypt and view the data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] A clear disadvantage related to symmetric encryption is that sensitive data can be leaked if the private key is spread to individuals that should not have access to the data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] However, given that only one key is involved in the encryption process it can generally be said that speed is an advantage of symmetric encryption.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Asymmetric encryption expands on symmetric encryption by incorporating two different types of keys into the encryption method: private and public keys.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] A public key can be accessed by anyone and is unique to one user whereas a private key is a secret key that is unique to and only known by one user.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] In most scenarios the public key is the encryption key whereas the private key is the decryption key.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] As an example, if individual A would like to send a message to individual B using asymmetric encryption, he would encrypt the message using Individual B's public key and then send the encrypted version.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Individual B would then be able to decrypt the message using his private key.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Individual C would not be able to decrypt Individual A's message, as Individual C's private key is not the same as Individual B's private key.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Asymmetric encryption is often described as being more secure in comparison to symmetric database encryption given that private keys do not need to be shared as two separate keys handle encryption and decryption processes.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] For performance reasons, asymmetric encryption is used in Key management rather than to encrypt the data which is usually done with symmetric encryption.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] The Symmetric & Asymmetric Database Encryption section introduced the concept of public and private keys with basic examples in which users exchange keys.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] The act of exchanging keys becomes impractical from a logistical point of view, when many different individuals need to communicate with each-other.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] In database encryption the system handles the storage and exchange of keys.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] If encryption keys are not managed and stored properly, highly sensitive data may be leaked.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Additionally, if a key management system deletes or loses a key, the information that was encrypted via said key is essentially rendered "lost" as well.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] The complexity of key management logistics is also a topic that needs to be taken into consideration.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] As the number of application that a firm uses increases, the number of keys that need to be stored and managed increases as well.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Thus it is necessary to establish a way in which keys from all applications can be managed through a single channel, which is also known as enterprise key management.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Enterprise Key Management Solutions are sold by a great number of suppliers in the technology industry.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] These systems essentially provide a centralised key management solution that allows administrators to manage all keys in a system through one hub.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Thus it can be said that the introduction of enterprise key management solutions has the potential to lessen the risks associated with key management in the context of database encryption, as well as to reduce the logistical troubles that arise when many individuals attempt to manually share keys.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Hashing is used in database systems as a method to protect sensitive data such as passwords; however it is also used to improve the efficiency of database referencing.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Inputted data is manipulated by a hashing algorithm.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] The hashing algorithm converts the inputted data into a string of fixed length that can then be stored in a database.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Hashing systems have two crucially important characteristics that will now be outlined.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Firstly, hashes are "unique and repeatable".
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] As an example, running the word "cat" through the same hashing algorithm multiple times will always yield the same hash, however it is extremely difficult to find a word that will return the same hash that "cat" does.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Secondly, hashing algorithms are not reversible.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] To relate this back to the example provided above, it would be nearly impossible to convert the output of the hashing algorithm back to the original input, which was "cat".
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] In the context of database encryption, hashing is often used in password systems.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] When a user first creates their password it is run through a hashing algorithm and saved as a hash.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] When the user logs back into the website, the password that they enter is run through the hashing algorithm and is then compared to the stored hash.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Given the fact that hashes are unique, if both hashes match then it is said that the user inputted the correct password.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] One example of a popular hash function is SHA-256.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] One issue that arises when using hashing for password management in the context of database encryption is the fact that a malicious user could potentially use an Input to Hash table rainbow table for the specific hashing algorithm that the system uses.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] This would effectively allow the individual to decrypt the hash and thus have access to stored passwords.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] A solution for this issue is to 'salt' the hash.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Salting is the process of encrypting more than just the password in a database.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] The more information that is added to a string that is to be hashed, the more difficult it becomes to collate rainbow tables.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] As an example, a system may combine a user's email and password into a single hash.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] This increase in the complexity of a hash means that it is far more difficult and thus less likely for rainbow tables to be generated.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] This naturally implies that the threat of sensitive data loss is minimised through salting hashes.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Some systems incorporate a "pepper" in addition to salts in their hashing systems.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Pepper systems are controversial, however it is still necessary to explain their use.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] A pepper is a value that is added to a hashed password that has been salted.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] This pepper is often unique to one website or service, and it is important to note that the same pepper is usually added to all passwords saved in a database.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] In theory the inclusion of peppers in password hashing systems has the potential to decrease the risk of rainbow (Input : Hash) tables, given the system-level specificity of peppers, however the real world benefits of pepper implementation are highly disputed.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] In application-level encryption, the process of encrypting data is completed by the application that has been used to generate or modify the data that is to be encrypted.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Essentially this means that data is encrypted before it is written to the database.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] This unique approach to encryption allows for the encryption process to be tailored to each user based on the information (such as entitlements or roles) that the application knows about its users.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] According to Eugene Pilyankevich, "Application-level encryption is becoming a good practice for systems with increased security requirements, with a general drift toward perimeter-less and more exposed cloud systems".
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] One of the most important advantages of application-level encryption is the fact that application-level encryption has the potential to simplify the encryption process used by a company.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] If an application encrypts the data that it writes/modifies from a database then a secondary encryption tool will not need to be integrated into the system.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] The second main advantage relates to the overarching theme of theft.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Given that data is encrypted before it is written to the server, a hacker would need to have access to the database contents as well as the applications that were used to encrypt and decrypt the contents of the database in order to decrypt sensitive data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] The first important disadvantage of Application-level encryption is that applications used by a firm will need to be modified to encrypt data themselves.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] This has the potential to consume a significant amount of time and other resources.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Given the nature of opportunity cost firms may not believe that application-level encryption is worth the investment.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] In addition, application-level encryption may have a limiting effect on database performance.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] If all data on a database is encrypted by a multitude of different applications then it becomes impossible to index or search data on the database.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] To ground this in reality in the form of a basic example: it would be impossible to construct a glossary in a single language for a book that was written in 30 languages.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Lastly the complexity of key management increases, as multiple different applications need to have the authority and access to encrypt data and write it to the database.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] When discussing the topic of database encryption it is imperative to be aware of the risks that are involved in the process.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] The first set of risks are related to key management.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] If private keys are not managed in an "isolated system", system administrators with malicious intentions may have the ability to decrypt sensitive data using keys that they have access to.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] The fundamental principle of keys also gives rise to a potentially devastating risk: if keys are lost then the encrypted data is essentially lost as well, as decryption without keys is almost impossible.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Encryption can be employed to enhance the security of data stored in a database by converting the information into an unreadable format using an algorithm.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] The encrypted data can only be accessed and deciphered with a decryption key, ensuring that even if the database is compromised, the information remains confidential.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] By encrypting sensitive data such as passwords, financial records, and personal information, organizations can safeguard their data from unauthorized access and data breaches.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] This process mitigates the risk of data theft and ensures compliance with data protection regulations.
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Implementing encryption in a database involves utilizing encryption technologies such as Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) or Transport Layer Security (TLS).
[src:encryption-at-rest/database-encryption] Encryption keys must be securely managed to prevent unauthorized decryption of data.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] The expression *full disk encryption (FDE)* (or *whole disk encryption*) signifies that everything on the disk is encrypted, barring the master boot record (MBR), or similar area of a bootable disk, with code that starts the operating system loading sequence.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Some hardware-based full disk encryption systems can truly encrypt an entire boot disk, including the MBR.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] With transparent encryption, the files are accessible immediately after the key is provided, and the entire volume is typically mounted as if it were a physical drive, making the files just as accessible as any unencrypted ones.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] No data stored on an encrypted volume can be read (decrypted) without using the correct password/keyfile(s) or correct encryption keys.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] The entire file system within the volume is encrypted (including file names, folder names, file contents, and other meta-data).
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] To be transparent to the end-user, transparent encryption usually requires the use of device drivers to enable the encryption process.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Although administrator access rights are normally required to install such drivers, encrypted volumes can typically be used by normal users without these rights.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] In general, every method in which data is seamlessly encrypted on write and decrypted on read, in such a way that the user and/or application software remains unaware of the process, can be called transparent encryption.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Disk encryption does not replace file encryption in all situations.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Disk encryption is sometimes used in conjunction with filesystem-level encryption with the intention of providing a more secure implementation.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Since disk encryption generally uses the same key for encrypting the whole drive, all of the data can be decrypted when the system runs.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] However, some disk encryption solutions use multiple keys for encrypting different volumes.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] If an attacker gains access to the computer at run-time, the attacker has access to all files.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Conventional file and folder encryption instead allows different keys for different portions of the disk.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Thus an attacker cannot extract information from still-encrypted files and folders.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Unlike disk encryption, filesystem-level encryption does not typically encrypt filesystem metadata, such as the directory structure, file names, modification timestamps or sizes.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Trusted Platform Module (TPM) is a secure cryptoprocessor embedded in the motherboard that can be used to authenticate a hardware device.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Since each TPM chip is unique to a particular device, it is capable of performing platform authentication.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] It can be used to verify that the system seeking the access is the expected system.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] A limited number of disk encryption solutions have support for TPM.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] These implementations can wrap the decryption key using the TPM, thus tying the hard disk drive (HDD) to a particular device.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] If the HDD is removed from that particular device and placed in another, the decryption process will fail.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Recovery is possible with the decryption password or token.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] The TPM can impose a limit on decryption attempts per unit time, making brute-forcing harder.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] The TPM itself is intended to be impossible to duplicate, so that the brute-force limit is not trivially bypassed.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Although this has the advantage that the disk cannot be removed from the device, it might create a single point of failure in the encryption.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] For example, if something happens to the TPM or the motherboard, a user would not be able to access the data by connecting the hard drive to another computer, unless that user has a separate recovery key.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] There are multiple tools available in the market that allow for disk encryption.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] However, they vary greatly in features and security.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] They are divided into three main categories: software-based, hardware-based within the storage device, and hardware-based elsewhere (such as CPU or host bus adaptor).
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Hardware-based full disk encryption within the storage device are called self-encrypting drives and have no impact on performance whatsoever.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Furthermore, the media-encryption key never leaves the device itself and is therefore not available to any malware in the operating system.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] The Trusted Computing Group Opal Storage Specification provides industry accepted standardization for self-encrypting drives.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] External hardware is considerably faster than the software-based solutions, although CPU versions may still have a performance impact, and the media encryption keys are not as well protected.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] There are other (non-TCGA/OPAL based) self-encrypted drives (SED) that don't have the known vulnerabilities of the TCG/OPAL based drives (see section below).
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] They are Host/OS and BIOS independent and don't rely on the TPM module or the motherboard BIOS, and their Encryption Key never leaves the crypto-boundary of the drive.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] All solutions for the boot drive require a pre-boot authentication component which is available for all types of solutions from a number of vendors.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] It is important in all cases that the authentication credentials are usually a major potential weakness since the symmetric cryptography is usually strong.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Secure and safe recovery mechanisms are essential to the large-scale deployment of any disk encryption solutions in an enterprise.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] The solution must provide an easy but secure way to recover passwords (most importantly data) in case the user leaves the company without notice or forgets the password.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Challenge–response password recovery mechanism allows the password to be recovered in a secure manner.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] It is offered by a limited number of disk encryption solutions.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] No secret data is exchanged during the recovery process.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Does not require a network connection, i.e. it works for users that are at a remote location.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] An emergency recovery information (ERI) file provides an alternative for recovery if a challenge–response mechanism is unfeasible due to the cost of helpdesk operatives for small companies or implementation challenges.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Most full disk encryption schemes are vulnerable to a cold boot attack, whereby encryption keys can be stolen by cold-booting a machine already running an operating system, then dumping the contents of memory before the data disappears.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] The attack relies on the data remanence property of computer memory, whereby data bits can take up to several minutes to degrade after power has been removed.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Even a Trusted Platform Module (TPM) is not effective against the attack, as the operating system needs to hold the decryption keys in memory in order to access the disk.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Full disk encryption is also vulnerable when a computer is stolen when suspended.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] As wake-up does not involve a BIOS boot sequence, it typically does not ask for the FDE password.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Hibernation, in contrast goes via a BIOS boot sequence, and is safe.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] All software-based encryption systems are vulnerable to various side channel attacks such as acoustic cryptanalysis and hardware keyloggers.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] In contrast, self-encrypting drives are not vulnerable to these attacks since the hardware encryption key never leaves the disk controller.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Also, most full disk encryption schemes don't protect from data tampering (or silent data corruption, i.e. bitrot).
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] That means they only provide privacy, but not integrity.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Block cipher-based encryption modes used for full disk encryption are not authenticated encryption themselves because of concerns of the storage overhead needed for authentication tags.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] One of the ways to mitigate these concerns, is to use file systems with full data integrity checks via checksums (like Btrfs or ZFS) on top of full disk encryption.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Full disk encryption has several benefits compared to regular file or folder encryption, or encrypted vaults.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] With full disk encryption, the decision of which individual files to encrypt is not left up to users' discretion.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] This is important for situations in which users might not want or might forget to encrypt sensitive files.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Immediate data destruction, such as simply destroying the cryptographic keys (crypto-shredding), renders the contained data useless.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] However, if security towards future attacks is a concern, purging or physical destruction is advised.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] One issue to address in full disk encryption is that the blocks where the operating system is stored must be decrypted before the OS can boot, meaning that the key has to be available before there is a user interface to ask for a password.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Most full disk encryption solutions utilize pre-boot authentication by loading a small, highly secure operating system which is strictly locked down and hashed versus system variables to check for the integrity of the pre-boot kernel.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] Some implementations such as BitLocker Drive Encryption can make use of hardware such as a Trusted Platform Module to ensure the integrity of the boot environment, and thereby frustrate attacks that target the boot loader by replacing it with a modified version.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] This ensures that authentication can take place in a controlled environment without the possibility of a bootkit being used to subvert the pre-boot decryption.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] With a pre-boot authentication environment, the key used to encrypt the data is not decrypted until an external key is input into the system.
[src:encryption-at-rest/disk-encryption] All these possibilities have varying degrees of security; however, most are better than an unencrypted disk.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] The **Linux Unified Key Setup** (**LUKS**) is a disk encryption specification created by Clemens Fruhwirth in 2004 and originally intended for Linux.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] LUKS implements a platform-independent standard on-disk format for use in various tools.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] This facilitates compatibility and interoperability among different programs and operating systems, and assures that they all implement password management in a secure and documented manner.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] The contents of the encrypted device are arbitrary, and therefore any filesystem can be encrypted, including swap partitions.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] There is an unencrypted header at the beginning of an encrypted volume, which allows up to 8 (LUKS1) or 32 (LUKS2) encryption keys to be stored along with encryption parameters such as cipher type and key size.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] The presence of this header is a major difference between LUKS and dm-crypt, since the header allows multiple different passphrases to be used, with the ability to change and remove them.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] If the header is lost or corrupted, the device will no longer be decryptable.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] Encryption is done with a multi-layer approach.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] First, the block device is encrypted using a *master key.* This master key is encrypted with each active *user key*.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] User keys are derived from passphrases, FIDO2 security keys, TPMs or smart cards.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] The multi-layer approach allows users to change their passphrase without re-encrypting the whole block device.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] Key slots can contain information to verify user passphrases or other types of keys.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] There are two versions of LUKS, with LUKS2 featuring resilience to header corruption, and using the Argon2 key derivation function by default, whereas LUKS1 uses PBKDF2.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] Conversion between both versions of LUKS is possible in certain situations, but some features may not be available with LUKS1 such as Argon2.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] Available cryptographic algorithms depend on individual kernel support of the host.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] Libgcrypt can be used as a backend for hashing, which supports all of its algorithms.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] It is up to the operating system vendor to choose the default algorithm.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] LUKS1 makes use of an anti-forensics technique called AFsplitter, allowing for secure data erasure and protection.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] Logical Volume Management can be used alongside LUKS.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] When LVM is used on an unlocked LUKS container, all underlying partitions (which are LVM logical volumes) can be encrypted with a single key.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] This is akin to splitting a LUKS container into multiple partitions.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] The LVM structure is not visible until the disk is decrypted.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] When LUKS is used to encrypt LVM logical volumes, an encrypted volume can span multiple devices.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] The underlying LVM volume group is visible without decrypting the encrypted volumes.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] A common usage of LUKS is to provide full disk encryption, which involves encrypting the root partition of an operating system installation, which protects the operating system files from being tampered with or read by unauthorized parties.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] On a Linux system, the boot partition (`/boot`) may be encrypted if the bootloader itself supports LUKS (e.g.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] This is undertaken to prevent tampering with the Linux kernel.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] However, the first stage bootloader or an EFI system partition cannot be encrypted (see Full disk encryption#The boot key problem).
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] On mobile Linux systems, postmarketOS has developed osk-sdl to allow a full disk encrypted system to be unlocked using a touch screen.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] For systems running systemd, the `systemd-homed` component can be used to encrypt individual home directories.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] The reference implementation for LUKS operates on Linux and is based on an enhanced version of cryptsetup, using dm-crypt as the disk encryption backend.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] Under Microsoft Windows, LUKS-encrypted disks can be used via the Windows Subsystem for Linux.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] Several Linux distributions allow the root device to be encrypted upon OS installation.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] These installers include Calamares, Ubiquity, Debian-Installer, and more.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] LUKS headers are backward compatible; newer versions of LUKS are able to read headers of previous versions.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] The LUKS2 header has a binary area and a JSON area, a second binary and JSON area, and a keyslots area.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] The binary and JSON areas are repeated two times with minor variations.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] The size of the binary areas is always 4kiB.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] The size of binary plus JSON area can be a power-of-two number of bytes between 16 kiB and 4 MiB, making the size of the JSON areas between 12 kiB and 4092 kiB each.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] The base LUKS2 JSON metadata object has 5 keys: *config*, *keyslots*, *digests*, *segments*, and *tokens*.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] The *tokens* object can hold additional for external systems integrating with LUKS.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] Userdata, *segments*, are encrypted with a large master-key and an efficient encryption algorithm.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] The master key can then be encrypted with a more expensive algorithm and potentially weaker user-provided keys, these encrypted master-keys are then stored in *Keyslots*.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] This slows brute-force attempts at guessing the password, and also allows changing decryption methods and passwords without having to reencrypt the entire data section, by only needing to rewrite the same master-key encrypted differently into the *keyslots*.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] Keyslots take up the device region after the two binary and JSON areas.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] In the typical case shown above this starts at 32 kiB, and runs up to 4 MiB or 16 MiB.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] Usually a device is spanned by a single *segment*, with the offset set to 16MiB and the size to dynamic.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] During reencryption or in unusual configuration there might be multiple segments that in total should span the device without gaps or overlap.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] The *segment*(s) should each have a single associated *digest*, that each have one or more associated *keyslots*.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] *Keyslots* may also be unassociated with any digest and used for other purposes.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] The default algorithm for *digests*, pbkdf2, as well as the anti-forensic stripes type "luks1", are identical to LUKS1.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] The key derivation defaults to stronger algorithms unsupported by LUKS1, but can be set to the supported pbkdf2.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] Cryptsetup is the reference implementation of the LUKS frontend.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] Re-encrypting a LUKS container can be done either with the `cryptsetup` tool itself, or with a legacy tool called `cryptsetup-reencrypt`.
[src:encryption-at-rest/linux-unified-key-setup] These tools can also be used to add encryption to an existing unencrypted filesystem, or remove encryption from a block device.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] VeraCrypt is a fork of the discontinued TrueCrypt project.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] It was initially released on 22 June 2013.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] Many security improvements have been implemented and concerns within the TrueCrypt code audits have been addressed.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] VeraCrypt includes optimizations to the original cryptographic hash functions and ciphers, which boost performance on modern central processing units.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] VeraCrypt employs AES, Serpent, Twofish, Camellia, and Kuznyechik as ciphers.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] Version 1.19 stopped using the Magma cipher in response to a security audit.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] The cryptographic hash functions available for use in VeraCrypt are BLAKE2s-256, SHA-256, SHA-512, Streebog and Whirlpool.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] VeraCrypt used to have support for RIPEMD-160, but it has since been removed in version 1.26.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] VeraCrypt's block cipher mode of operation is XTS.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] It generates the header key and the secondary header key (XTS mode) using PBKDF2 with a 512-bit salt.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] By default, they go through 200,000 or 500,000 iterations, depending on the underlying hash function used and whether it is system or non-system encryption.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] The user can customize it to lower these numbers to as low as 2,048 and 16,000, respectively.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] QuarksLab conducted an audit of version 1.18 on behalf of the Open Source Technology Improvement Fund (OSTIF), which took 32 man-days.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] The auditor published the results on 17 October 2016.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] On the same day, IDRIX released version 1.19, which resolved major vulnerabilities identified in the audit.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] Fraunhofer Institute for Secure Information Technology (SIT) conducted another audit in 2020, following a request by Germany's Federal Office for Information Security (BSI), and published the results in October 2020.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] In March 2026, VeraCrypt’s lead developer Mounir Idrassi disclosed that Microsoft had terminated the developer account used to digitally sign the software’s Windows drivers and UEFI bootloader.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] As a result, no new Windows releases could be published; Linux and macOS updates remained unaffected.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] The same issue affected other Windows applications, including WireGuard, MemTest86, and Windscribe.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] Idrassi stated that he had attempted to sign Windows drivers for version 1.26.27 in January 2026, but his account was terminated with an automated message stating his company “did not meet verification requirements” – without specifics or any appeal mechanism.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] The certificate authority (CA) used for existing signatures was set to be revoked in late June 2026.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] Idrassi warned that Windows systems with Secure Boot enabled might then fail to load VeraCrypt’s bootloader, which may have rendered encrypted drives unbootable unless the CA issue was resolved.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] As of April 10 2026, Microsoft restored Idrassi's access to his Microsoft Partner Center account, allowing him to sign new versions.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] Idrassi then released a VeraCrypt 1.26.28 maintenance release with newly Microsoft-signed EFI bootloader components for current 1.26.x users, so people do not have to wait for VeraCrypt 1.27.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] The old VeraCrypt bootloader will still work even after the certificate expires, but future Windows configurations may require bootloaders signed with the new certificate.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] There are several kinds of attacks to which all software-based disk encryption is vulnerable.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] As with TrueCrypt, the VeraCrypt documentation instructs users to follow various security precautions to mitigate these attacks, several of which are detailed below.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] VeraCrypt stores its keys in random-access memory (RAM); on some personal computers dynamic random-access memory (DRAM) will maintain its contents for several seconds after power is cut, or longer if the temperature is lowered.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] Even if there is some degradation in the memory contents, various algorithms may be able to recover the keys.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] This method, known as a cold boot attack, which would apply in particular to a notebook computer obtained while in power-on, suspended, or screen-locked mode, was successfully used to attack a file system protected by TrueCrypt versions 4.3a and 5.0a in 2008.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] With version 1.24, VeraCrypt added the option of encrypting the in-RAM keys and passwords on x86-64 editions of Microsoft Windows, with a CPU overhead of less than 10%, and the option of erasing all encryption keys from memory when a new device is connected.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] VeraCrypt documentation states that VeraCrypt is unable to secure data on a computer if an attacker physically accessed it and VeraCrypt is then used on the compromised computer by the user again.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] This does not affect the common case of a stolen, lost, or confiscated computer.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] Therefore, physical security is a basic premise of a secure system.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] Some kinds of malware are designed to log keystrokes, including typed passwords, that may then be sent to the attacker over the Internet or saved to an unencrypted local drive from which the attacker might be able to read it later, when they gain physical access to the computer.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] VeraCrypt does not take advantage of Trusted Platform Module (TPM).
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] VeraCrypt FAQ repeats the negative opinion of the original TrueCrypt developers verbatim.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] The TrueCrypt developers were of the opinion that the exclusive purpose of the TPM is "to protect against attacks that require the attacker to have administrator privileges, or physical access to the computer".
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] The attacker who has physical or administrative access to a computer can circumvent TPM, e.g., by installing a hardware keystroke logger, by resetting TPM, or by capturing memory contents and retrieving TPM-issued keys.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] The condemning text goes so far as to claim that TPM is entirely redundant.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] It is true that after achieving either unrestricted physical access or administrative privileges, it is only a matter of time before other security measures in place are bypassed.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] However, stopping an attacker in possession of administrative privileges has never been one of the goals of TPM.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] (See Trusted Platform Module § Uses for details.) TPM might, however, reduce the success rate of the cold boot attack described above.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] TPM is also known to be susceptible to SPI attacks.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] As with its predecessor TrueCrypt, VeraCrypt supports plausible deniability by allowing a single "hidden volume" to be created within another volume.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] The Windows versions of VeraCrypt can create and run a hidden encrypted operating system whose existence may be denied.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] The VeraCrypt documentation lists ways in which the hidden volume deniability features may be compromised (e.g., by third-party software which may leak information through temporary files or via thumbnails) and possible ways to avoid this.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] VeraCrypt supports parallelized encryption for multi-core systems.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] On Microsoft Windows, pipelined read and write operations (a form of asynchronous processing) to reduce the performance hit of encryption and decryption.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] On processors supporting the AES-NI instruction set, VeraCrypt supports hardware-accelerated AES to further improve performance.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] On 64-bit CPUs VeraCrypt uses optimized assembly implementation of Twofish, Serpent, and Camellia.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] VeraCrypt was forked from the since-discontinued TrueCrypt project in 2013, and originally contained mostly TrueCrypt code released under the TrueCrypt License 3.0.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] In the years since, more and more of VeraCrypt's code has been rewritten and released under the permissive Apache License 2.0.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] The TrueCrypt license is generally considered to be source-available but not free and open source.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] The Apache license is universally considered to be free and open source.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] The mixed VeraCrypt license is widely but not universally considered to be free and open source.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] On 28 May 2014 TrueCrypt ceased development under unusual circumstances, and there exists no way to contact the former developers.
[src:encryption-at-rest/veracrypt] VeraCrypt has been used by consumers of child pornography to conceal illicit materials, with the FBI being unable to decrypt the encrypted content, leading to requests by prosecutors to force the defendants to hand over their passwords under the *foregone conclusion* doctrine of the All Writs Act.
